statistical learning framework, learner observes training data \(\{(x_i, y_i)\}_{=1}^n\) drawn unknown distribution \(\mathcal{D}\) selects hypothesis \(h\) class \(\mathcal{H}\) minimize expected loss:\[\begin{equation}
\min_{h \\mathcal{H}} \; \mathbb{E}_{(x,y) \sim \mathcal{D}} \left[ \ell(h(x), y) \right]
\tag{24.1}
\end{equation}\]natural game-theoretic interpretation. learner Player 1, choosing \(h\). Nature Player 2, choosing \((x, y)\). loss function \(\ell\) payoff matrix — learner minimizes , nature maximizes . minimax theorem guarantees zero-sum formulation, optimal learning strategies exist.

online learning, decisions made sequentially. round \(t\), learner chooses action \(a_t\) set \(\mathcal{}\), observes loss vector \(\ell_t()\) actions. cumulative regret played action \(\) :\[\begin{equation}
R_T() = \sum_{t=1}^{T} \ell_t(a_t) - \sum_{t=1}^{T} \ell_t()
\tag{24.2}
\end{equation}\]-regret algorithm ensures \(\max_a R_T() / T \0\) \(T \\infty\). celebrated connection game theory : players zero-sum game use -regret algorithms, time-averaged strategies converge Nash equilibrium (Cesa-Bianchi & Lugosi, 2006).

Regret matching (Hart & Mas-Colell, 2000) one simplest -regret algorithms. round, player computes cumulative regret action plays proportionally positive regrets:\[\begin{equation}
\sigma_t() = \begin{cases}
R_t^+() \,/\, \sum_{'} R_t^+(') & \text{} \sum_{'} R_t^+(') > 0 \\
1 / |\mathcal{}| & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\tag{24.3}
\end{equation}\]\(R_t^+() = \max(0, R_t())\). algorithm building block counterfactual regret minimization (CFR), covered ??.

Markov decision process (MDP) tuple \((\mathcal{S}, \mathcal{}, P, R, \gamma)\) :\(\mathcal{S}\) finite set states,\(\mathcal{}\) finite set actions,\(P(s' \mid s, )\) transition probability,\(R(s, , s')\) reward function,\(\gamma \[0, 1)\) discount factor.agent’s goal find policy \(\pi(\mid s)\) maximizes expected cumulative discounted reward:\[\begin{equation}
V^\pi(s) = \mathbb{E}_\pi \left[ \sum_{t=0}^{\infty} \gamma^t R_t \;\middle|\; S_0 = s \right]
\tag{25.1}
\end{equation}\]

optimal value function \(V^*(s)\) satisfies Bellman optimality equation:\[\begin{equation}
V^*(s) = \max_{\\mathcal{}} \sum_{s'} P(s' \mid s, ) \left[ R(s, , s') + \gamma \, V^*(s') \right]
\tag{25.2}
\end{equation}\]Equivalently, optimal action-value function \(Q^*(s, )\) satisfies:\[\begin{equation}
Q^*(s, ) = \sum_{s'} P(s' \mid s, ) \left[ R(s, , s') + \gamma \max_{'} Q^*(s', ') \right]
\tag{25.3}
\end{equation}\]

Q-learning (Watkins & Dayan, 1992) model-free, -policy algorithm. taking action \(\) state \(s\), observing reward \(r\) next state \(s'\):\[\begin{equation}
Q(s, ) \leftarrow Q(s, ) + \alpha \left[ r + \gamma \max_{'} Q(s', ') - Q(s, ) \right]
\tag{25.4}
\end{equation}\]\(\max\) operator makes -policy: Q-learning updates toward best possible next action regardless actually taken. standard conditions, \(Q \Q^*\).

SARSA (State-Action-Reward-State-Action) -policy alternative bootstraps action \('\) actually chosen, rather greedy \(\max\):\[\begin{equation}
Q(s, ) \leftarrow Q(s, ) + \alpha \left[ r + \gamma \, Q(s', ') - Q(s, ) \right]
\tag{25.5}
\end{equation}\]SARSA learns value policy follows (including exploration), making conservative near dangerous states.

