q_agent_create <- function(n_actions, alpha = 0.1, epsilon = 0.1) {
  Q <- rep(0, n_actions)
  list(
    choose = function() {
      if (runif(1) < epsilon) {
        sample(n_actions, 1)
      } else {
        ties <- which(Q == max(Q))
        sample(ties, 1)
      }
    },
    update = function(action, reward) {
      Q[action] <<- Q[action] + alpha * (reward - Q[action])
    },
    get_Q = function() Q
  )
}

text:
independent learner (IL) maintains Q-values \(Q_i(a_i)\) actions , 26. ignores opponent entirely.joint-action learner (JAL) observes opponent’s action round maintains Q-values joint action profile: \(Q_i(a_i, a_{-})\). agent also tracks empirical model opponent’s action frequencies \(\hat{\pi}_{-}(a_{-})\) selects actions maximize expected payoff model:\[\begin{equation}
a_i^* = \arg\max_{a_i} \sum_{a_{-}} \hat{\pi}_{-}(a_{-}) \, Q_i(a_i, a_{-})
\tag{27.1}
\end{equation}\]JAL addresses non-stationarity adapting strategy opponent’s observed behavior. However, still assumes opponent’s policy stationary — assumption breaks agents learning.

two-player zero-sum games, Littman (1994) proposed minimax-Q, replaces \(\max\) operator Q-learning minimax calculation. Instead learning deterministic best action, agent learns mixed strategy \(\pi_i\) maximizes worst-case expected payoff:\[\begin{equation}
V_i = \max_{\pi_i} \min_{a_{-}} \sum_{a_i} \pi_i(a_i) \, Q_i(a_i, a_{-})
\tag{27.2}
\end{equation}\]Q-value update becomes:\[\begin{equation}
Q_i(a_i, a_{-}) \leftarrow Q_i(a_i, a_{-}) + \alpha \left[ r_i + \gamma \, V_i - Q_i(a_i, a_{-}) \right]
\tag{27.3}
\end{equation}\]stateless (matrix game) setting, \(\gamma = 0\) update simplifies :\[\begin{equation}
Q_i(a_i, a_{-}) \leftarrow Q_i(a_i, a_{-}) + \alpha \left[ r_i - Q_i(a_i, a_{-}) \right]
\tag{27.4}
\end{equation}\]key insight Q-values converge game’s payoff matrix, minimax strategy Q-values converges Nash equilibrium mixed strategy.

