first-price auction, bidding truthfully guarantees zero profit. Bidders must therefore shade bids. derive equilibrium, suppose bidders follow increasing strategy \(b(v)\). Bidder \(\) valuation \(v_i\) wins others lower valuations. \(v_j \sim \text{Uniform}(0, 1)\), probability winning bid \(b\) \(F(b^{-1}(b))^{N-1} = (b^{-1}(b))^{N-1}\).Maximizing expected payoff \((v_i - b) \cdot \Pr(\text{win})\) imposing boundary condition \(b(0) = 0\) yields symmetric Bayesian Nash equilibrium:\[\begin{equation}
b^*(v) = \frac{N - 1}{N} \cdot v
\tag{32.1}
\end{equation}\]bidder shades bid factor \(1/N\). \(N \\infty\), bids converge valuations — competition eliminates bidder’s surplus. \(N = 2\), bidders bid half valuation; \(N = 10\), bid 90% valuation.

formats, expected revenue equals expected second-highest order statistic. \(N\) bidders \(v_i \sim \text{Uniform}(0, 1)\), expected value \(k\)-th order statistic \(k/(N+1)\), :\[\begin{equation}
\mathbb{E}[\text{revenue}] = \mathbb{E}[v_{(N-1)}] = \frac{N - 1}{N + 1}
\tag{32.2}
\end{equation}\]example, \(N = 5\) bidders, expected revenue \(4/6 \approx 0.667\).

