Definition: Nash Bargaining SolutionThe Nash bargaining solution selects feasible payoff pair maximizes Nash product:\[\begin{equation}
(u_1^*, u_2^*) = \arg\max_{(u_1, u_2) \S} (u_1 - d_1)(u_2 - d_2)
\tag{35.1}
\end{equation}\]subject \(u_1 \geq d_1\) \(u_2 \geq d_2\).Nash (1950) showed unique solution satisfying four axioms:Pareto efficiency — feasible outcome makes players strictly better .Symmetry — problem symmetric, solution gives equal payoffs.Independence irrelevant alternatives (IIA) — removing feasible outcomes chosen change solution.Scale invariance — solution invariant positive affine transformations utility.linear frontier \(u_1 + u_2 = v\) disagreement point \((0, 0)\), Nash bargaining solution gives player \(v / 2\) — equal split.

players different bargaining powers \(\alpha\) \(1 - \alpha\) (\(\alpha \(0, 1)\)), asymmetric Nash bargaining solution maximizes generalized Nash product:\[\begin{equation}
(u_1^*, u_2^*) = \arg\max_{(u_1, u_2) \S} (u_1 - d_1)^\alpha (u_2 - d_2)^{1-\alpha}
\tag{35.2}
\end{equation}\]

Rubinstein (1982) modeled bargaining sequential game. Two players take turns proposing split surplus size 1. Player 1 proposes odd periods, Player 2 even periods. player discount factor \(\delta_i \(0, 1)\) — waiting costly.Theorem: Rubinstein EquilibriumThe unique subgame perfect equilibrium alternating-offers game gives Player 1 share:\[\begin{equation}
x_1^* = \frac{1 - \delta_2}{1 - \delta_1 \delta_2}
\tag{35.3}
\end{equation}\]Player 2 receives \(1 - x_1^*\). \(\delta_1 = \delta_2 = \delta\), split converges \((1/2, 1/2)\) \(\delta \1\).intuition patient player (higher \(\delta\)) obtains larger share can credibly wait longer. first-mover advantage shrinks players become patient.

Given \(n\) agents utilities \(u_1, u_2, \ldots, u_n\) allocation \(x\), define three standard social welfare functions (SWFs):Utilitarian SWF — maximize total welfare:
\[\begin{equation}
W_U(x) = \sum_{=1}^{n} u_i(x)
\tag{38.1}
\end{equation}\]Rawlsian (maximin) SWF — maximize welfare worst-agent:
\[\begin{equation}
W_R(x) = \min_{} \; u_i(x)
\tag{38.2}
\end{equation}\]Nash SWF — maximize product utilities (equivalent Nash bargaining equal bargaining power):
\[\begin{equation}
W_N(x) = \prod_{=1}^{n} u_i(x)
\tag{38.3}
\end{equation}\]Pareto efficiencyAn allocation \(x\) Pareto efficient alternative \(x'\) \(u_i(x') \geq u_i(x)\) \(\) strict inequality least one. three SWF optima lie Pareto frontier, generally select different points.

